The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Industrialist S.K. Birla met chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee at Writers? Buildings on Tuesday afternoon to discuss the construction of an information technology and management institute on Diamond Harbour Road in collaboration with B.M. Khaitan.

 irla informed Bhattacharjee that the work would start in around four months? time and be completed before the 2008 academic session begins. The institute will come up on a 15-acre plot at a cost of Rs 50 crore.

 Two men were killed in separate accidents in Shibpur, Howrah, on Tuesday. Ramdeo, 35, a milkman, was run over on GT Road by a minibus as it hit his cycle. He died on the spot. On Carey Road, 27-year-old Amit Roychowdhury was crushed under the rear wheels after falling off a bus.

 A crack was detected in the railway tracks at Howrah station on Tuesday. Eastern Railway officials said a Tarakeswar-Howrah local train was entering platform 5 around 11.15 am when the driver detected the crack. The train entered the platform after the crack was repaired around 11.50 am.

 Sumitra Haldar, 50, was run over by a truck at Rajdanga, in the Kasba police station area, on Tuesday morning. According to police, the mishap took place while Haldar, a greengrocer, was crossing a road with her merchandise. She was taken to a local hospital, where she was declared dead. The driver fled with the vehicle.

 Shantanu Karmakar, 13, a resident of Budge Budge, was reported missing on Monday evening. He had gone for a dip in the Hooghly with his friends. Police fear that the boy has drowned. 

 Residents of Thakurpukur on Tuesday morning demonstrated in front of a nursing home, alleging medical negligence leading to the death of a newborn. The baby?s father has lodged a complaint with police, demanding action against the doctors allegedly responsible for the death. 

 Rafiq Khan, 42, died after suffering an electric shock in his Watgunge home on Monday night. Khan had put his hand in a bucket of water that was being warmed with an immersion heater. He was taken to SSKM Hospital, where he died on Tuesday morning.

 Rakesh Mistry, 18, committed suicide by consuming poison in Ashoknagar, near Tollygunge, on Tuesday. According to police, Mistry?s girlfriend had told him of her engagement with another man earlier in the day. Two of his friends took him to hospital.

 Members of the Calcutta University Employees? Unity Centre have urged the university authorities to make alternative arrangements for those employees who do not want mobile phones as gifts on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the institution. Registrar Samir Bandyopadhyay said the proposal to present mobile phones to employees had not been finalised.

 Renal transplant patients and their family members will take part in a rally on March 9 to observe World Kidney Day. Indian Association of Kidney Patients, a voluntary organisation, has organised the rally. 

